From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] sky2: ack Baikal IRQ block in ISR pre-handler

v79 enabled BAR+0x204 (full Baikal IRQ enable) and BAR+0x54 (per-IRQ
mask), but link still stayed DOWN and SMI controller stuck.  Live BAR
readback showed BAR+0x50 with bit 0x40000 ("AN failed / MAC idle")
pending unacked.

Sky2's existing ISR reads its own Yukon-2 status registers at offset
0x108 (B0_Y2_SP_ISRC2) and never touches Baikal's BAR+0x50.  The
Baikal MAC raises bit 0x40000, MSI is delivered, sky2's ISR fires,
sees zero in B0_Y2_SP_ISRC2, exits — leaving 0x40000 asserted at the
PIC level.  The MAC stays in "interrupt pending → clocked down" state
and the SMI bus dies.

v80: pre-ack any pending Baikal IRQ bits at the top of sky2_intr, and
return IRQ_HANDLED (not IRQ_NONE) if sky2's Yukon-2 status came back
zero on Baikal — the IRQ probably came from BAR+0x50 only.

Pass criterion: SMI register reads should stay live indefinitely
(not degrade to echo-of-last-write), link should reach UP and ping
192.168.50.95 should reply.
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
@@ -3151,9 +3151,30 @@ static irqreturn_t sky2_intr(int irq, void *dev_id)
 	struct sky2_hw *hw = dev_id;
 	u32 status;

+#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
+	/* PS4 Baikal: ack any pending Baikal-specific IRQ bits before
+	 * sky2's Yukon-2 path runs.  Bit 0x40000 in BAR+0x50 is the MAC's
+	 * "AN failed / idle" event — sky2 doesn't know about it, and
+	 * leaving it asserted at the PIC level keeps the MAC clocked-down
+	 * and the SMI controller wedged.  We ack indiscriminately; sky2
+	 * doesn't otherwise touch BAR+0x50. */
+	if (sky2_is_baikal(hw)) {
+		u32 bstat = sky2_read32(hw, 0x50);
+		if (bstat)
+			sky2_write32(hw, 0x50, bstat);
+	}
+#endif
+
 	/* Reading this mask interrupts as side effect */
 	status = sky2_read32(hw, B0_Y2_SP_ISRC2);
 	if (status == 0 || status == ~0) {
 		sky2_write32(hw, B0_Y2_SP_ICR, 2);
+#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
+		/* On Baikal the IRQ may have come from BAR+0x50 only — claim
+		 * it as handled instead of returning IRQ_NONE so the kernel
+		 * doesn't disable the IRQ line on too many spurious returns. */
+		if (sky2_is_baikal(hw))
+			return IRQ_HANDLED;
+#endif
 		return IRQ_NONE;
 	}
